<!-- 3.3.13 -->
<div class='toload proposition'>
	<p><span class='envidentifier'>Proposition 3.3.13</span>
	Let $X$ be a locally compact Hausdorff space, $\left\{x_n\right\}_n$ be a sequence of elements of $X$, $\left\{U_n\right\}_n$ a sequence of open subsets of $X$ such that
	<ol class='roman'>
		<li>
			$x_n\in U_n$;
		</li>
		
		<li>
			$U_n\cap U_m=\varnothing$ for all $n\neq m$.
		</li>
	</ol>
	Let $H$ be a Hausdorff first-countable locally path-connected topological space and consider $\left\{g_n:U_n\to H\right\}$ a family of continuous functions such that $g_n(x_n)$ converges to some $t\in H$. Then
	<ol class='alphpar'>
		<li>
			There exists a continuous function $f:X\to H$ such that $f(x_n)=g_n(x_n)$ for all sufficiently large $n$, and $f(x)=t$ for all $x\not\in\bigcup_n U_n$.
		</li>
		
		<li>
			if $H=\mathbb{R}$, there is a continuous function $f:X\to H$ such that $f=g_n$ on a neighbourhood of $x_n$ and $f(x)=t$ for all $x\not\in\bigcup_n U_n$.
		</ol>
	</ol>
	(Note that it is not necessary to take subsequences!)
	</p>
</div>